premise_source_doc_sentence: Helike  (  -LSB- ˈhɛlᵻkiː -RSB- Ἑλίκη , pronounced -LSB- heˈlikɛː -RSB- , modern -LSB- eˈlici -RSB-  )  was an ancient Greek city that was submerged by a tsunami in the winter of 373 BC .
Selinus  (  Greek : Σελινούς , Modern : Σελινούντας Selinountas  )  was a native mythical king of Aigaleia in Achaea  (  the modern prefecture  )  .
Modern research attributes the catastrophe to an earthquake and accompanying tsunami which destroyed and submerged the city .
In Greek mythology , Helike  (  -LSB- ˈhɛlᵻkiː -RSB- Ἑλίκη , pronounced -LSB- heˈlikɛː -RSB- , modern -LSB- eˈlici -RSB-  )  was a name of several women .
It was located in Achaea , northern Peloponnesos , two kilometres  (  12 stadia  )  from the Corinthian Gulf and near the city of Boura , which , like Helike , was a member of the Achaean League .
